Name: Mission Hill Saloon
Description: Cash-only joint with a jukebox & a pool table serving beer & shots in basic, old-school surrounds.

Name: Shotwell's
Description:
The first known owner of 3349 20th Street was Ms. Marie Grother. It is not known if she was a widow or a single woman owner.
1891: 
Two German immigrant businessmen rented the property from Ms. Grother and Schlicht-mann & Bredhofy “Grocery Saloon” opened their doors. Many German immigrants ran gro-cery stores in the West during this time, often with a “back room grog shop.”

Name: Gangway
Description: One of the City's oldest gay bars with a rich history of activism.  C.f. https://savingplaces.org/stories/gangway-san-franciscos-104-year-old-dive-bar#.Vj0BoCssNB8 viewed Nov. 6, 2015

Name: Elixir
Description: From 1858 this has been a saloon, but during Prohibition is was known as a "soft drink parlor."

Name: Homestead
Description: Neighborhood bar with a fireplace and peanut shells on the floor, a broad whiskey selection, and Prohibition-Era decor.

Name: The Saloon
Description: SF's oldest saloon, blues bar, saved in the 1906 earthquake

Name: Alembic
Description: Classic handcrafted cocktails & an inventive bar food menu in a dimly lit, rustic space with booths.

Name: Northstar Cafe
Description: Low-key bar pulling in sports fans, especially folks rooting for the Buffalo Bills & Sabres.

Name: Old Ship Saloon

Name: Dogpatch Saloon

Name: Hotel Utah
Description:
It was built in 1908, when the Barbary Coast was still going strong. 1908, the year Bette Davis was born. The year of the first Model T. Twenty-eight years before the Bay Bridge. This bar was standing before, during, and after Prohibition.
 
The Deininger family opened the saloon, and commissioned furniture makers in Belgium to design and create its ornate bar-back. They also served the city’s best beer, Fredericksburg, brought to The Utah by horse and carriage and lowered into the cellar in wooden kegs.

Gamblers, thieves, ladies up to no good, politicians, hustlers, friends of opium, goldseekers, godseekers, charlatans, police, fancy miscreants — they all visited The Utah. And that was when South of Market was just a lonely section of the San Francisco waterfront.
 
After the Bay Bridge was finished in 1936, SOMA came into its own. The saloon (and the hotel upstairs) was home to longshoremen, merchants, metal smiths, furniture makers, with traffic flowing back and forth between San Francisco and the East Bay.

Name: La Rocca's Corner
Description:
Long ago, a popular San Francisco hangout was La Rocca's Corner, a North Beach bar at Columbus and Taylor that's been around since the end of Prohibition.

Everyone went there: fishermen, showgirls, politicos, athletes, celebrities, even mobsters. It was at La Rocca's that Nick DeJohn, a Chicago racketeer, had his last drink in 1947 before he was found stuffed in his car trunk. And it was at La Rocca's barely 20 years later that socialite Gordon Getty met his sophisticated wife Ann.

It was that kind of place.

Name: Buena Vista Cafe
Description: Opened in 1916, this corner spot serves its signature Irish coffee alongside American staples.
